<div class="container-fluid main-container">




<div id="header">



<h1 class="title toc-ignore">STAT 8561 Linear Statistical Analysis Final Project: Comprehensive Analyses of Tumor Size Data under Different Treatements</h1>
<h4 class="author">Elif KIR</h4>
<h4 class="date">12/09/2021</h4>

</div>


<div id="libraries" class="section level2">
<h2>Libraries</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>library(leaps)
library(MASS)
library(olsrr)
library(MPV)
library(stats)
library(car)
library(pls)
library(tidyverse)
set.seed(1923)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="uploading-datasets" class="section level2">
<h2>Uploading Datasets</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>data_tumor_raw=read.table(&quot;tumor_size.txt&quot;)
colnames(data_tumor_raw)=c(&quot;y&quot;,&quot;x1&quot;,&quot;x2&quot;,&quot;x3&quot;,&quot;x4&quot;,&quot;x5&quot;) #name columns of dataset
data_tumor=data_tumor_raw  #a copy of original data set to make operations on
colnames(data_tumor)=c(&quot;y&quot;,&quot;x1&quot;,&quot;x2&quot;,&quot;x3&quot;,&quot;x4&quot;,&quot;x5&quot;) #name columns of dataset

head(data_tumor)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##         y      x1      x2      x3      x4 x5
## 1  93.433  5.9701  6.0470  8.1105 1.70843  1
## 2 104.456  9.3506  9.4063  8.3650 0.34726  1
## 3 163.792  9.7180  9.4967 16.8862 4.76446  1
## 4 125.249 14.1317 13.9422 14.8049 2.19965  2
## 5 146.837  9.9278 10.0581 14.1477 2.80567  1
## 6  78.196  1.9318  1.6575 15.9753 7.58081  1</code></pre>
<p><strong><em>Explanation</em></strong></p>
<p>In data set, Y is the tumor size (in mm) after 4 different treatments. The variables are defined as follows:</p>
<p>X1 = the amount of dosage for treatment 1 X2 = the amount of dosage for treatment 2 X3 = the amount of dosage for treatment 3 X4 = the coded amount of dosage for treatment 4 X5 = Three different types of tumor.</p>
</div>
<div id="a-use-all-your-knowledge-to-build-the-best-regression-model-and-estimate-all-coefficients-of-the-model-notice-that-your-score-will-depend-on-how-well-you-can-use-the-various-methods-that-are-taught-in-this-class." class="section level2">
<h2>(a) Use all your knowledge to build the best regression model and estimate all coefficients of the model (notice that your score will depend on how well you can use the various methods that are taught in this class).</h2>
<pre class="r"><code>##Strategy for Variable Selection and Model Building

##Step 1: Fit the largest model possible to the data and perform thorough analysis

data_tumor$x5=as.factor(data_tumor$x5) ##since x5 is an indicator variable
model=lm(y~.,data=data_tumor)
summary(model)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ ., data = data_tumor)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -36.328  -7.070  -0.701   6.620  44.861 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(&gt;|t|)    
## (Intercept)   29.797      5.903   5.048 1.57e-06 ***
## x1            15.500      7.187   2.157   0.0330 *  
## x2           -14.327      8.660  -1.654   0.1006    
## x3             9.497      2.992   3.174   0.0019 ** 
## x4           -12.219      5.820  -2.099   0.0378 *  
## x52          -50.563      2.913 -17.356  &lt; 2e-16 ***
## x53          -32.570      3.825  -8.514 4.90e-14 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 13.69 on 123 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8747, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8686 
## F-statistic: 143.2 on 6 and 123 DF,  p-value: &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>anova(model)##MSRES 187.</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: y
##            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq  F value    Pr(&gt;F)    
## x1          1  83472   83472 445.5298 &lt; 2.2e-16 ***
## x2          1     84      84   0.4457   0.50563    
## x3          1  15100   15100  80.5971 3.907e-15 ***
## x4          1    913     913   4.8718   0.02915 *  
## x5          2  61363   30682 163.7636 &lt; 2.2e-16 ***
## Residuals 123  23045     187                       
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: Intercept and the regressors of x1,x3,x4,x52,x53 are statistically significant and adjusted R2 is 86.7%.Pvalue is almost 0 and this says regression is signifcant.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: Intercept and the regressors of x1,x3,x4,x52,x53 are statistically significant and adjusted R2 is 86.7%.Pvalue is almost 0 and this says regression is signifcant.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>##Step 2: Residual Analysis

#Normal Probability Plot of Residuals
Rstudent_residual = rstudent(model)
sorted_Rstudent_residual=sort(Rstudent_residual)

p_i=matrix(NA,nrow=1,ncol=length(sorted_Rstudent_residual))
for(i in 1:length(sorted_Rstudent_residual)){
  p_i[[i]]=(i-0.5)/length(sorted_Rstudent_residual)
}

plot(x=sorted_Rstudent_residual,y=p_i[1,],xlim =c(-4,4),ylim=c(0,1),main=&#39;Normal Probability Plot of the Residuals&#39;)
abline(lm(p_i[1,]~sorted_Rstudent_residual))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>qqnorm(sorted_Rstudent_residual,xlim = c(-4,4),ylim = c(-4,4),main=&#39;Normal Q-Q Plot of the Residuals&#39;)
qqline(sorted_Rstudent_residual)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: Deviations exist in the upper and the lower tails. There are problems with the normality of the residuals.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: Deviations exist in the upper and the lower tails. There are problems with the normality of the residuals.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#Plot of Residuals against the Fitted Values

yhat = model$fit 
plot(x=yhat,y=Rstudent_residual)
abline(0,0)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: First there is a nonlinear pattern in the graph and resiudals for some observations are out of a certain band such as of -2,2. It can be say that these observations having studentized residuals are greater than 2 and smaller than -2 are potential outliers and need further analyses. Also, nonlinear pattern in the graph indicates transformation on the regressors and/or response variable may be needed to deal with this nonlinear pattern in the graph.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: First there is a nonlinear pattern in the graph and resiudals for some observations are out of a certain band such as of -2,2. It can be say that these observations having studentized residuals are greater than 2 and smaller than -2 are potential outliers and need further analyses. Also, nonlinear pattern in the graph indicates transformation on the regressors and/or response variable may be needed to deal with this nonlinear pattern in the graph.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#Check Partial Regression Graph 
avPlots(model = model,marginal.scale = T,id=T)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: In Added-Variable plots, there is a problem with linearity for x1 and x2 variables since all the points are located at almost the same point. This may indicate a sort of collinearity. X4 also needs further analyses.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: In Added-Variable plots, there is a problem with linearity for x1 and x2 variables since all the points are located at almost the same point. This may indicate a sort of collinearity. X4 also needs further analyses.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#Pair plots of x1 and x2

plot(data_tumor$x1,data_tumor$x2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: Almost a perfect linearity between x1 and x2.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: Almost a perfect linearity between x1 and x2.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#Pair plots of x1 and x4

plot(data_tumor$x1,data_tumor$x4)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="960" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>&quot;Comment: There is a linear pattern to some extent between x1 and x4. To understand the seriousness of multicollinearity, further tests are needed.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Comment: There is a linear pattern to some extent between x1 and x4. To understand the seriousness of multicollinearity, further tests are needed.&quot;</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>#Pair plots of x2 and x4

<pre class="r"><code>#Predicted R square
pred_r_squared &lt;- function(linear.model) {
  lm.anova &lt;- anova(linear.model)
  tss &lt;- sum(lm.anova$&#39;Sum Sq&#39;)
  pred.r.squared &lt;- 1-PRESS(linear.model)/(tss)
  return(pred.r.squared)
}

pred_r_squared((reg_pca))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0.9357576</code></pre>
<p><strong><em>FINAL COMMENT:</em></strong> Comment: Final model is PCA regression using first 7 component as features. To understand variables contribution, PCA components could be interpreted. For exmaple, first component represents the effect of tumor type 2, which is x52==1 in the data. The second component represents x1 and x2 against other features. The important point here is that PCA behaves x1 and x2 as a only one feature. It is probably because of their multicollinearity. Based on other components we can conclude variable x4 has a weak contribution to the model,which is the variable of coded amount of dosage for treatment 4.On the other hand, during my all analyses, I end up with x3 is a significant variable.</p>
<p>In regression components, 5 and 7 are not significant. Adjusted Rsquare is 95%, which is pretty good. Model gives stable results. We see that MSE for prediction results is 2.99, which is really small just like MSE in part e. So we can conclude that model is reliable for extrapolation as well as interpolation. Predicted adjusted Rsquare is around 94%, which also shows the models performance in prediction. Finally, the model tries to use all information in the one of the most efficient ways and handle the hugest problem in the data, multicollinearity. We can conclude that based on the tumor type, the amount of the dosage from different treatments matters since they have a correlation with the size of the tumor!</p>
